<p>
  Experience only ever arrives as this moment — and most of a day is spent fleeing
  it: rehearsing conversations, repairing an image, hunting the next reason to feel
  settled. Careers unfinished, relationships pending, repairs still waiting: none
  of that cancels the quieter fact. Every experience is shaped by the mind that
  meets it. If attention is elsewhere, or if confusion is the weather of the hour,
  no outward success will feel like success.
</p>

<p>
  Overthinking, in the sense that names this site, is not simply thinking a lot.
  It is thought that keeps elaborating without returning to what is actually present —
  planning as evasion, rumination as identity, cleverness that never lands. The early
  Buddhist texts are unusually precise about that habit. They treat it not as a
  personality flaw but as a trainable pattern: craving, clinging, and the stories the
  mind builds around both.
</p>

<p>
  Nothing here is final. These are notes, not conclusions.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>Not a worldview to swallow</h2>

<p>
  These pages are a working record of sitting with the Buddhist tradition long enough
  for parts of it to become usable — not a temple, not a course, and not a substitute
  for a teacher, a community, or sustained practice. The tradition is old, vast, and
  internally diverse. What appears here draws primarily from the Pali canon — the
  earliest surviving body of Buddhist teaching — while remaining attentive to what
  later traditions developed, contested, and corrected.
</p>

<p>
  Clear seeing into attention, where it is genuine, still does not settle what the
  universe is made of, how politics should go, or what happens after death. The texts
  themselves often ask to be tested against experience rather than believed on
  authority. Where interpretation hardens into certainty on these pages, treat that
  as a draft that has not yet been revised.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>A diagnosis that can be checked</h2>

<p>
  Ordinary sources of satisfaction are not worthless — and they are not reliable enough.
  Pleasure fades into indifference or irritation; security requires constant maintenance;
  even a good day becomes the memory of a good day. Most of a life can be spent seeking
  better conditions without noticing that the search itself is structured by how attention
  moves. The early discourses begin further upstream: with
  <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
  named as the problem, not as a verdict that existence is worthless. The
  <a href="/suttas/dhammacakkappavattana/">Four Noble Truths</a>
  are a frame to apply — what hurts, what drives it, that it can end, and how — rather
  than a creed to swallow whole.
</p>

<p>
  The mechanism they point to is
  <span class="pali" data-pali="tanhā" data-en="craving">tanhā</span>:
  thirst. Wanting and not-wanting trade places all afternoon. A favorite meal becomes
  too much; sun on the skin becomes heat; shade becomes chill.
  <span class="pali" data-pali="upadāna" data-en="clinging">Upadāna</span>
  then consolidates the reach into holding — mine, my view, my story — and the pattern
  keeps producing a self who must defend it. Against that pressure the tradition asks
  that experience be seen through the
  <a href="/concepts/ti-lakkhana/">three characteristics</a> —
  <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span> —
  not as slogans worn on the sleeve, but as what shows up when craving loosens.
</p>

<p>
  The response is training, not a metaphysical settlement: the
  <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>,
  often gathered as the
  <a href="/concepts/three-trainings/">three trainings</a>
  of
  <span class="pali" data-pali="sīla" data-en="virtue">sīla</span>,
  <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="concentration">samādhi</span>, and
  <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">paññā</span>.
  Ethics steadies the mind; stillness clarifies seeing; seeing changes how one lives.
  The path spirals. The rest of the site takes those movements apart; this page only
  needs to name the pressure.
</p>

<blockquote>
  "Monks, I do not say that the attainment of wisdom is all at once. Rather, the
  attainment of wisdom is by gradual training, gradual practice, gradual progress."
  <cite>— MN 70 (adapted)</cite>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<h2>Why the Pali stays visible</h2>

<p>
  The words appear in an ochre tint with a dotted underline. They are not ornaments.
  Pali is the language in which the earliest surviving Buddhist teachings were preserved,
  and English renderings are always approximations. A term like
  <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
  is routinely flattened to "suffering," which misses registers the English word does
  not carry. A term like
  <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
  has been so thoroughly domesticated into wellness culture that meeting it in its
  original context can feel like meeting a stranger you thought you already knew.
</p>

<p>
  Click any highlighted Pali word for a short note on the term and its closest English
  sense. On larger screens the notes appear in the right margin; on a phone they expand
  inline. Several can stay open at once. The same notes are collected in the
  <a href="/glossary/">glossary</a>.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>Saved passages</h2>

<p>
  Select a stretch of text on any article and tap the bookmark that appears in the gutter.
  The highlight stays; click it later to open a private note. Passages live in this browser
  only — clear site data and they go with it — so the
  <a href="/saved/">saved passages</a>
  page can export Markdown if you want a backup or a copy on another device.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>Where to begin</h2>

<p>
  If you are not sure where to start, use the
  <a href="/guide/">Guide</a> — a suggested trajectory through ethics, unification, and
  wisdom as one spiral, not a sit-first ladder. Formal sitting appears later in Foundations
  as a laboratory among the
  <a href="/concepts/three-trainings/">three trainings</a>, not as the summit of the path.
  Beyond that, the site divides into four main sections.
  <a href="/concepts/">Concepts</a>
  takes up core ideas one at a time.
  <a href="/suttas/">Suttas</a>
  looks at specific discourses: what they contain, how they are structured, what they ask
  of the reader.
  <a href="/thoughts/">Thoughts</a>
  is the less tidy section — longer pieces where something is still being worked out.
  <a href="/quotes/">Quotes</a>
  collects passages worth sitting with.
</p>

<p>
  Everything here is a draft in the sense that understanding changes. If something seems
  wrong or is missing important nuance, that is probably because the draft has not caught
  up yet. What the path asks is not another belief system, but a clearer contact with
  how craving and confusion actually work while they are happening. The path spirals.
</p>
